CAISO data¶

This workbook analyses CAISO demand data along with generation from renewables (wind and solar only) in an attempt to determine how much storage (and at what duration) may be needed in the California markets as grid penetration of renewable generation assets (again, speicfically wind and solar) increases.

Key Questions to be addressed:¶

  • High-level assessment of the current state of energy in CA (energy produced in a 1-year period, peak demand, and the current fraction of overall delivered energy that has come from wind and solar)
  • How much energy needs to be shifted and by how long and for what level of renewable penetration?
  • What is the optimal mix of wind and solar on the grid and how does that optimum vary based on extent of renewable penetration?

Data Cleaning¶

Data for a 1-year period (from July 1, 2018 to June 30, 2019), have been sourced from CAISO. These data contain information on total demand in the CAISO region, along with production from wind and solar plants.

# Create a function to convert 'Date Time' column from str datatype to datetime datatype
def new_time(df):
    # Parse time column 
    df['Year']   = df['Date Time'].str[0:4]
    df['Month']  = df['Date Time'].str[5:7]
    df['Day']    = df['Date Time'].str[8:10]
    df['Hour']   = df['Date Time'].str[11:13]
    df['Minute'] = df['Date Time'].str[14:16]

    # Create list of columns that will be converted to datetime datatype
    time = ['Year','Month','Day','Hour','Minute']

    # Convert to datetime
    df['Time']   = pd.to_datetime(df[time].astype(str).apply(' '.join, 1), format='%Y %m %d %H %M')
    df['Time']   = df['Time'].dt.tz_localize('UTC').dt.tz_convert('US/Pacific')

    # Append original Date Time column to list of columns to be dropped
    time.append('Date Time')

    # Drop time columns that are no longer needed
    df.drop(time,axis=1,inplace=True)
    return(df)

Assessment of energy in the CAISO region¶

Evaluate data to determine:

  • Peak power demand
  • Total energy demand in this time period
  • Total energy from wind and solar, along with capacity factors
  • Variability:
    • Hour-to-hour (intraday)
    • Day-to-day (within a month)
    • Seasonally (within the year)
    • Note that there may be some longer-term variations that are not captured in these data (e.g., weather patterns that exist on a multi-year cycle, such as $el$ $ni\tilde{n}o$)

# Write function to add columns to facilitate plotting visualization

def net_energy_cols(df):
    df['Minus Wind (MW)']  = df['Demand (MW)'] - df['Wind (MW)']
    df['Minus Solar (MW)'] = df['Minus Wind (MW)'] - df['Solar (MW)']
    df['Net Demand (MW)']  = df['Minus Solar (MW)']
    return df

myFmt = mdates.DateFormatter('%H:%M',tz=pytz.timezone("US/Pacific"))

# Write function for plotting data
def energy_plot(df,start,end):
    x = df[(df.Time > start) & (df.Time < end)]

    plt.plot(x.Time,x['Minus Solar (MW)'], linewidth=3, color='gold');
    plt.fill_between(x.Time, x['Minus Wind (MW)'], x['Minus Solar (MW)'], facecolor='gold', alpha=0.2, interpolate=True)

    plt.plot(x.Time,x['Minus Wind (MW)'], linewidth=3, color='royalblue');
    plt.fill_between(x.Time, x['Demand (MW)'], x['Minus Wind (MW)'], facecolor='royalblue', alpha=0.2, interpolate=True)

    plt.plot(x.Time,x['Demand (MW)'], linewidth=3, color='black');
    plt.fill_between(x.Time, x['Net Demand (MW)'], 0, where=x['Net Demand (MW)']>0, facecolor='black',alpha=0.2, interpolate=True)
    
    ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(myFmt)
    plt.axis([start, end,0,50000]);

How much energy needs to be shifted and by how long?¶

In this section, we'll scale the production of renewables to determine how much energy would need to be shifted and by how long. As part of this analysis, we'll also take a look at the optimal blend of renewables on the grid, i.e. to minemize the amount of shifting required. This will proceed using the following approach (psuedo-code):

  • Set a desired amount of energy that must come from renewables
  • Determine how much energy needs to be shifted for an array of wind / solar compositions
  • Determine the minimum amount of time that each packet of energy needs to be shifted
  • Assume the data are static and periodic within the year so the beginning of the data set (i.e., where renewable generation is relatively low) can draw from data toward the end of the dataset, where renewable generation is higher.

Let's start by looking at what generation curves would look like for a hand-picked day in the Spring if all of the energy for that day were to come from renewables (first wind and solar separately, then a 50/50 mix).

In [23]:
# To start, we need to define a few new dataframes that support these mixes
# To do this, the wind and solar columns will be scaled by total installed capacity

# Dataframe that assumes wind only
df_wind = df[['Time','Demand (MW)','Wind (MW)','Solar (MW)']].copy()
df_wind['Wind (MW)'] = df_wind['Wind (MW)'] / wind_capacity
df_wind['Solar (MW)'] = 0

# Dataframe that assumes solar only
df_solar = df[['Time','Demand (MW)','Wind (MW)','Solar (MW)']].copy()
df_solar['Solar (MW)'] = df_solar['Solar (MW)'] / solar_capacity
df_solar['Wind (MW)'] = 0

# Dataframe that assumes a 50/50 mix of solar and wind

df_both['Solar (MW)'] = df_both['Solar (MW)'] / solar_capacity

Next, we'll want to look at how much energy needs to be shifted, and by how far. In doing so, we'll also solve for the optimal mix of renewables on the grid at a given renewable adoption rate. As an initial pass, it is assumed that both wind and solar are the same cost (which is roughly true right now, at $1/W installed), thus this assessment is made based on capacity, rather than explicitly on capital.

Psuedo code:

  • Define a desired amount of power to come from renewables (start at 10% and go in increments of 10% up to 100%)
  • Look at the entire year and determine intervals where there is a surplus or deficit of energy
  • Until surplus = deficit = 0:
    • Shift the charge one time step (wrapping around)
    • Fill defecit with charge capacity
    • Keep track of how many minutes / hours the energy has been shifted
In [29]:
# Define function to determine the optimal mix of renewables on the grid for a given reneable penetration
def opt_mix(x_renewables,df_temp):
        
    # adjust the mix of wind and solar 
    pct_solar  = np.linspace(0,1,101)

    excess = []
    
    for solar in pct_solar:

        scaler = energy_total * x_renewables / (solar * energy_solar + (1-solar) * energy_wind)
        
        df_temp['Solar (MW)'] = df_temp['Solar (MW) Base'] * scaler * solar
        df_temp['Wind (MW)']  = df_temp['Wind (MW) Base'] * scaler * (1-solar)
        
        df_temp = net_energy_cols(df_temp)
                        
        excess.append(df_temp[df_temp['Net Demand (MW)'] < 0].sum()['Net Demand (MW)'])
    
    return excess

In [38]:
# Define function to determine how much energy needs to be shifted and by how long
def storage(df_temp,x_renewables,x_solar):

    scaler = energy_total * x_renewables / (x_solar * energy_solar + (1-x_solar) * energy_wind)

    df_temp['Solar (MW)'] = df_temp['Solar (MW) Base'] * scaler * x_solar
    df_temp['Wind (MW)']  = df_temp['Wind (MW) Base'] * scaler * (1-x_solar)
    
    df_temp = df_temp.groupby(df_temp.index // 12).sum()

    df_temp = net_energy_cols(df_temp)
    
    df_shift = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Excess','Shortage'])
    df_shift['Temp'] = np.linspace(0,0,df_temp.shape[0]).astype(int)

    df_shift['Excess']   = -1*df_temp[df_temp['Net Demand (MW)'] < 0]['Net Demand (MW)']
    df_shift['Shortage'] = df_temp[df_temp['Net Demand (MW)'] > 0]['Net Demand (MW)']
    df_shift.fillna(0,inplace=True)
    
    
    time_shifted = 0
    results = []
    
    n = 0
        
    while df_shift['Excess'].sum() > 1:

        wrap = df_shift.iloc[-1]['Excess']
        df_shift['Excess'] = df_shift['Excess'].shift(periods=1)
        df_shift['Excess'].loc[0] = wrap
        df_shift['Temp'] = df_shift.loc[:, ['Excess', 'Shortage']].min(axis=1)

        time_shifted += 5
        energy_shifted = df_shift['Temp'].sum()
        results.append((time_shifted,energy_shifted))

        df_shift['Excess'] = df_shift['Excess'] - df_shift['Temp']
        df_shift['Shortage'] = df_shift['Shortage'] - df_shift['Temp']
        df_shift['Temp'] = 0
        
        n+=1
        
        if n%100 == 0:
            print('Periods Shifted: {}     Energy Shift Remaining: {} TWh'.format(n,round(df_shift['Excess'].sum()*p2e/M2T,1)))


    return results

df_duration = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Time Shifted (hrs)'])

frac_renewables = np.linspace(0,1,21)
cols = list(df_shift.columns)[1:]

for p in frac_renewables:
    column = str(int(round(100*p))) + '% Renewables'
    df_duration[column] = np.linspace(0,5,6)*np.nan

df_duration.fillna(0,inplace=True)

sum_lims = [0,2,4,10,100,1000]

i = 0

for col in df_duration.columns[1:]:
    for i in range(len(sum_lims)):
        if i == len(sum_lims)-1:
            total_shift = df_shift[col].iloc[sum_lims[i]:].sum()
            df_duration[col].iloc[i] = total_shift
        else:
            total_shift = df_shift[col].iloc[sum_lims[i]:sum_lims[i+1]].sum()
            df_duration[col].iloc[i] = total_shift
    print(col, 'column complete.')
